SIMPLE: invade
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Invade
<hw>In*vade"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Invaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Invading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>invadere</ets>,
<ets>invasum</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>vadere</ets> to go,
akin to E. <ets>wade</ets>: cf. OF. <ets>invader</ets>, F.
<ets>envahir</ets>. See <er>Wade</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To go into or upon; to pass within the confines of;
to enter; -- used of forcible or rude ingress.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which becomes a body, and doth then <qex>invade</qex>⟦br⟧
The state of life, out of the grisly shade.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enter with hostile intentions; to enter with a
view to conquest or plunder; to make an irruption into; to attack;
<as>as, the Romans <ex>invaded</ex> Great Britain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such an enemy⟦br⟧
Is risen to <qex>invade</qex> us.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To attack; to infringe; to encroach on; to violate;
<as>as, the king <ex>invaded</ex> the rights of the
people</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To grow or spread over; to affect injuriously and
progressively; <as>as, gangrene <ex>invades</ex> healthy
tissue</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To attack; assail; encroach upon. See
<er>Attack</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Invade
<hw>In*vade"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make an invasion.</def>
<rj><au>Brougham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Invader</ent>⟦br⟧
